      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer606919968" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11375946149432082956">It is no surprise, coming from an amazing author who has proven himself to be a master at delivering a story of pure emotion, that this new novel would be yet another abstract and truly compelling read.<br/><br/>Here, we have an eloquent narrator who is telling the tale of a man name Jim. What is interesting about the anonymous man who’s offering up Jim’s story is the fact that he exudes every emotion for his subject - from friendship to love to absolute nausea in a matter of paragraphs. <br/><br/>It is July of 198</span>
  <span id="freeText11375946149432082956" style="display:none">It is no surprise, coming from an amazing author who has proven himself to be a master at delivering a story of pure emotion, that this new novel would be yet another abstract and truly compelling read.<br /><br />Here, we have an eloquent narrator who is telling the tale of a man name Jim. What is interesting about the anonymous man who’s offering up Jim’s story is the fact that he exudes every emotion for his subject - from friendship to love to absolute nausea in a matter of paragraphs. <br /><br />It is July of 1983 when this writer and Jim meet up with each other for the first time. Inside the ‘End of the World Saloon,’ these two men make up the only inhabitants of the Bahamas watering hole (except for a large bartender), and thus their relationship begins. Upon meeting, Jim immediately utilizes his talents for being the perfect salesmen. Turning on the charm, offering a few crass statements and more than a bit of ego, the narrator doesn’t really like Jim, but he does hang on every word. <br /><br />As the tale unfolds so does the world of Jim. He is what you would call the ultimate schemer. He is the bearer of gifts and the bringer of dreams, but even though he may use back-alley tactics, his smile and eloquence makes up for that. <br /><br />Watching Jim rise up the ladder of wealth, he leaves more than a few broken hearts and empty pocketbooks behind, destroying client after client and making himself a target of government investigators. Like all rats from a sinking ship, Jim cuts and runs, finding himself in the Brazilian Amazon linked to a gold-mining operation.<br /><br />When a woman enters the picture, an ambitious and equally shady human named Mara, Jim’s views seem to alter, as battles begin to rage dealing with everything from regrets to a life that is sure to be over very soon. <br /><br />This is not a novel for the weary. This is not a novel for the cut-and-run reader who wishes to solve the puzzle and move on. This is a tale that must be read slowly so that all the emotion, eroticism, oddities, good and evil are understood as they’re released at the top of the writer’s lungs. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11375946149432082956" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


