<div id="review_633428222" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/633428222" />
    <a title="Robsy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13475525-robsy"><img alt="Robsy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1492027469p2/13475525.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/633428222?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robsy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robsy" href="/user/show/13475525-robsy">Robsy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer633428222" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16925241402258483874">If you like your women needy and overly sexed and your men desolate and pitiful, this is your book! You are also in for a treat if you like graphic descriptions of 22 on 80 year old passionate encounters! Gross!<br/>This begs the question of why I even finished this book that I picked up on a whim from my library. The writing is smooth and it starts out promising. Plus, it&apos;s a short book.<br/> I was just disgusted with the people in it. It begins with an adventure in the Bahamas, but slowly devolves into </span>
  <span id="freeText16925241402258483874" style="display:none">If you like your women needy and overly sexed and your men desolate and pitiful, this is your book! You are also in for a treat if you like graphic descriptions of 22 on 80 year old passionate encounters! Gross!<br />This begs the question of why I even finished this book that I picked up on a whim from my library. The writing is smooth and it starts out promising. Plus, it's a short book.<br /> I was just disgusted with the people in it. It begins with an adventure in the Bahamas, but slowly devolves into a story about a depraved man who goes through a series of ridiculous women. <br />I've constructed in my head a scenario that the author, Fred Waitzkin, is a frustrated comic book writer stuck in the year 1961 because his women are overly sexed, beautiful, absurdly needy, and hell-bent on pleasing the debased, handsome protagonist. Then he's celebrated at the end. Yuck! <br />Example: the one smart, halfway-to-normal-but-still-moneycrazed-and-sexedup woman in the entire novel is being choked by Jim, the main character, but instead of fighting, "She yielded. She hung like a rag. She gave herself to him." <br /><br />What the what!!? <br /><br />Again, two stars for a talented story-teller, but I came away thinking this renowned writer has issues with women. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16925241402258483874" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


