<div id="review_835568573" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/835568573" />
    <a title="Garryvivianne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/796518-garryvivianne"><img alt="Garryvivianne" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/835568573?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Garryvivianne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Garryvivianne" href="/user/show/796518-garryvivianne">Garryvivianne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer835568573" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13871832654769239769">A writer meets Jim, a man who seems to have everything, money, a fancy home, a beautiful wife, a big boat &amp; many stories to go with it. They become friends &amp; Jim all this time is telling his stories. Of growing up so poor, of becoming the breadwinner for his mother &amp; siblings. He finds he can sell anything &amp; really likes it. <br/><br/>Jim is making so much money, due mainly thru pyramid schemes, taking peoples&apos; money &amp; they thinking they are going to be rich so quick. Jim does not bother with peoples&apos; fee</span>
  <span id="freeText13871832654769239769" style="display:none">A writer meets Jim, a man who seems to have everything, money, a fancy home, a beautiful wife, a big boat &amp; many stories to go with it. They become friends &amp; Jim all this time is telling his stories. Of growing up so poor, of becoming the breadwinner for his mother &amp; siblings. He finds he can sell anything &amp; really likes it. <br /><br />Jim is making so much money, due mainly thru pyramid schemes, taking peoples' money &amp; they thinking they are going to be rich so quick. Jim does not bother with peoples' feelings, he is charismatic, good looking &amp; everybody likes &amp; trusts him. He is making so much money! <br /><br />He asks his writer friend to write his story, so they meet up all the time &amp; Jim just talks &amp; tells his tales. The writer knows all of Jim's wives' &amp; then ex-wives. He doesn't even seem to care about his wife, whoever it is at the time. <br /><br />But all the wealth does not last. When the writer meets up with Jim later on in life, Jim is poor, but he is so alive because of a young woman he has living with him. Jim has met Mara, a beautiful Israeli girl &amp; he is infatuated. The girl moves to Florida with him &amp; takes her two children. Mara dotes on Jim, no matter how old he looks now, how flabby &amp; slow he is. He is rejuvenated by Mara. Their sexual life is so active &amp; the writer &amp; Jim's ex-wife are afraid that he will die during sex. And they wonder if that is what Mara wants. Does she think he still has all the money that he talks about so much? <br /><br />Jim's stories are pretty interesting, do people really DO all these things? And do people really accumulate all the wealth in the world &amp; not worry about it? I was worried about how it would end, would Mara be at Jim's funeral, living with her ex-husband, living with the writer? You sometimes feel sorry for Jim, but then you don't! <br /><br />But I did like the ending of the book. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13871832654769239769" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


