<div id="review_485655578" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/485655578" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1301028-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1216778165p2/1301028.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/485655578?book_show_action=true">Dec 26, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/1301028-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781250011374" href="/book/show/15994617-the-dream-merchant">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1301028-michael?shelf=read-in-2013">read-in-2013</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1301028-michael?shelf=library-journal">library-journal</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer485655578" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13891142403481054676">This review originally ran in the 2/15/13 issue of <i>Library Journal</i>:<br/><br/>Waitzkin, best known for his chess memoir, Searching for Bobby Fischer, offers in his first novel an elusive lead character, a born salesman whose greatest glory is never far behind his latest failure. When we meet him, Jim is an old man, broke and alienated from his friends, wives, and business partners. The sole exceptions are Mara, a young Israeli woman whose intense sexual appetites may belie a sinister self-interest, and the</span>
  <span id="freeText13891142403481054676" style="display:none">This review originally ran in the 2/15/13 issue of <i>Library Journal</i>:<br /><br />Waitzkin, best known for his chess memoir, Searching for Bobby Fischer, offers in his first novel an elusive lead character, a born salesman whose greatest glory is never far behind his latest failure. When we meet him, Jim is an old man, broke and alienated from his friends, wives, and business partners. The sole exceptions are Mara, a young Israeli woman whose intense sexual appetites may belie a sinister self-interest, and the narrator, piecing together the story of Jim's life. But once upon a time, Jim was a king, moving from one elaborate scam to another, ruler of his own Brazilian gold empire. VERDICT The obvious comparison is to Joseph Conrad's Heart of Darkness, but readers of Philip Roth's Zuckerman novels will recognize Waitzkin's approach.<br /><br />Copyright ©2013 Library Journals LLC, a wholly owned subsidiary of Media Source, Inc. Reprinted with permission.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13891142403481054676" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


